  "articleSummary": "**Summary:**  \nThe article argues that “just adding more engineers” is a fallacy rooted in the quadratic growth of communication overhead (n · (n‑1)/2), which quickly outweighs any gains in capacity. It cites classic research—from Brooks’s *Mythical Man‑Month* to modern studies in *Accelerate* and IEEE—that shows larger teams suffer higher coordination costs, longer onboarding times, and slower delivery, while small, autonomous teams (5‑9 people, the “two‑pizza” rule) consistently outperform them in speed and quality. The piece is aimed at engineering managers, VP‑level leaders, and senior developers, using a mix of analytical tone and vivid metaphors (e.g., “tattooed formula,” “communication paths”) to warn against naïve scaling and to promote lean team structures.",
